ive name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire (Eure) and Ferrières (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferris","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Ó Fearghuis</b> or <b>Ó Fearghasa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fearghus</i>’, or from the Scottish-Gaelic form of this personal name, <i>Fearghus</i> (see   Fergus  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure and Ferrières, La Manche in Normandy, France."]},{"name":"Ferridge","meanings":["English: unexplained; possibly a form of  <i>Ferris</i> and therefore a variant of   Ferrers  ."]}]},{"name":"Amicia","type":"FIRST","meanings":["French: Beloved"],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":16,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":26,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":36,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Amicia de Ferrers was born in 1070, in Derbyshire, England. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Nigel de Stafford. She died in 1135, in Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1070–1135":"1070–1135","1068–1115":"1068–1115","1094–1165":"1094–1165","1105–1166":"1105–1166","1107–Female":"1107–Surnud","1165":"1165","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1070":"1070","1107":"1107","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1115":"1115","about 1107":"umbes 1107","1135":"1135","1068":"1068","1166":"1166","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burton upon Tren